<p class="entry-meta"><time class="entry-time" itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2014-11-19T02:15:08+00:00">November 19, 2014</time> By <span class="entry-author" itemprop="author" itemscope="itemscope" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><a href="http://causesofebolavirus.net/author/pasqualebrennan/" class="entry-author-link" itemprop="url" rel="author"><span class="entry-author-name" itemprop="name">Pasquale Brennan</span></a></span> <span class="entry-comments-link"><a href="http://causesofebolavirus.net/what-is-ebola-disease/#respond">Leave a Comment</a></span> </p></header><div class="entry-content" itemprop="text"><a href="http://causesofebolavirus.net/what-is-ebola-disease/" title="What Is Ebola Disease?"><img width="150" height="150" src="http://causesofebolavirus.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/What_Is_Ebola_Disease_2-150x150.jpg" class="alignleft" alt="What Is Ebola Disease?" itemprop="image" /></a><p>Ebola is considered a severe and lethal disease caused by a virus. In general, its common symptoms are comprised of fever, vomiting, diarrhea, bleeding, and then causing death. Ebola is able to occur in primates (gorillas, chimpanzees, and monkeys), and humans. The 2014 Ebola outbreak right in West Africa is listed as the largest one [&hellip;]</p>
